# FILE CHANGE SAFETY RULES

- Modify ONLY files related to the current task
- Do NOT reformat code unless required
- Do NOT delete files unless explicitly instructed
- Do NOT rename files without approval

If changes exceed task scope â†’ STOP.

---

# PULL REQUEST RULES

Automation MAY prepare a pull request but MUST NOT merge it.

PR description MUST include:

- Ticket number
- Brief summary of changes
- List of affected areas/modules
- Test status (added / updated / not required)

Example PR body:

### Ticket
TT-421

### Summary
Implemented calendar slot drag-and-drop functionality

### Affected Areas
- CalendarGridComponent
- DragDropService

### Tests
- Unit tests added

# MERGE SAFETY RULES

- NEVER auto-merge
- NEVER force-push
- NEVER resolve merge conflicts automatically
- NEVER rebase unless explicitly instructed

If conflicts exist â†’ STOP and report.

# TAGGING & VERSIONING

- Do NOT create tags unless instructed
- Do NOT invent version numbers
- Follow existing repository conventions

# ROLLBACK & RECOVERY

If an error is detected:

- Do NOT rewrite Git history
- Do NOT force-push
- Create a corrective commit instead

# FAILURE CONDITIONS (MUST STOP)

STOP and ask for clarification if:

- Ticket number is missing
- Working branch is incorrect
- Command affects protected branches
- Change scope exceeds the assigned task

# SUCCESS CRITERIA

- Clean, readable commit history
- Every commit traceable to a ticket
- No unintended file changes
- Review-ready pull requests

# FINAL RULE

Git automation must behave like a disciplined engineer, not a script.



